Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant will comply with all federal, and state laws, and local alcohol, drug and violence ordinances during the period of this Agreement.  If there is a case charging a violation of a criminal statute or local ordinance pending when this agreement is due to expire, this agreement continues in effect until 30 days after such case is revolved.  If the Defendant is charged with a criminal offense in a case subsequent to the Court's approval of this agreement, a finding of probable cause in that case is sufficient basis for termination of this agreement. 

Defendant will continue to comply with all bail or bond conditions ordered by the Court while this agreement is in effect. 

Probation - Comply with all conditions of probation for Count 3.  Violation of any rule of probation, or revocation from probation, constitutes a violation of this condition.

Defendant will keep Douglas County Clerk of Courts informed of his address and telephone number at all times, and stipulates that the sending of notice by regular mail to the address on file with the Clerk of Courts constitutes sufficient notice of any court hearings scheduled in this matter.  The non-appearance of the defendant may result in the issuance of an arrest warrant.

Defendant will complete the 27 week Men's Nonviolence Class at Domestic Abuse Intervention Programs (DAIP) in Duluth, MN. Mandatory orientations are held once a month.  Information is available at 218-722-2781, ext.106, or at www.theduluthmodel.org.  The Defendant will provide proof of completion of the program to the DA's Office within thirty (30) days of completion of the program.  The defendant will be truthful with the DAIP staff and inform the program staff of the current charge in this case and any domestic abuse charges in other pending or resolved cases.

If, despite good faith effort made by the Defendant, the program cannot be completed prior to the expiration of this deferred agreement, it is the responsibility of the Defendant, either personally or through his or her attorney, to contact the DA's Office at 715-395-1218 to request an extension of this deferred agreement. 

The DA's Office has sole discretion whether to modify this agreement to accommodate such a request.  Failure to request an extension in this circumstance constitutes evidence that the Defendant has not made good faith efforts to complete the program prior to expiration of this agreement.

11:03 AM Defendant Dominic Andrew Saling Sr. in court.  Attorney Joseph Foster Rosenthal in court for Dominic Andrew Saling Sr.  Attorney Angela M Wilson in court for State of Wisconsin. Attorney Rosenthal received amended information. For Count 1, defendant enter a DJOC for a period of two years. For Count 3, 60 days jail imposed and stayed for 2 years probation. Conditions of probation include comply with all programming as deemed necessary by the DOC. Count 2 to be dismissed. State has complied with victim's rights. Signature bond conditions to be amended to no violent or abusive contact victim 1. Defendant pleads not contest to Count 1 and Count 3. For Count 3, Attorney Rosenthal stipulates to a factual basis. Court accepts the Defendant's plea and finds that the Defendant's plea has been freely, voluntarily and intelligently made. The Defendant understands all the rights he is waiving by his plea. The Defendant is found guilty and Judgment of Conviction is entered. For Count 1, the Defendant is found guilty and Judgment of Conviction is deferred pursuant to the terms of the agreement. Court amends signature bond of $1,500 to no violent or abusive contact with Victim #1.

For Count 1, the judgment of conviction is deferred for a period of 2 years. Count 2 is dismissed. Court imposes for Count 3, 60 days jail imposed and stayed for 2 years probation.
